I came here a long time ago and was evidently so meh about the place that I didn't even bother to write a review. I recently revisited the place and even though I don't think the place has changed very much, I really, really dig the place now. A friend and I got a cafe, cafe au lait, a morning bun, and a rocher. The morning bun is so solid. It's got a bit of orange zest that really spices up the flavor. The bun is also super soft and delicious and not overwhelmingly sweet which is a problem that I usually experience with morning buns. I also really loved my latte--probably the best latte that I've had in awhile. Seating in the place is pretty limited though. We went around 11am and all the tables were filled so we had to stay at the standing bar. Traffic does flow in and out fairly consistently though so we were able to find a table pretty soon afterwards. tldr; super nice cafe with delicious morning buns and lattes--would definitely frequent if I was from the area

I was not a fan of pecan pies until I ate the one from Tartine. The pecans were perfectly roasted. The filling was not the thick overly sweet gooey but had just the right amount of sweetness. The day after my visit to Tartine I dipped into the large, fruit-filled bread pudding ($7) I'd purchased under the guise it was "for others". I dipped into it and polished it off and no "others" ever knew it was there. That's saying something (oink) as I'm not the biggest fan of baked sweets. Walking into Tartine on a weekday I was thrilled to find a short line which didn't even extend to the entrance. Considering weekend lines run out the door and down the block I'd advise a weekday visit. If you're lucky, you'll even land table seating. I settled on the richest sandwich in the history of mankind: the Pecorino & Almond ($13). It surprised me when served, as it was what I'd call a sandwich-and-a-half. That is, 3-half sandwiches when only 1 of those halves would've been ample. So, if you order this sandwich thinking that $13 is a steep price for a schmancy grilled cheese (albeit one with Sheep's milk, olive oil, lemon, and sage) think again. This sucker is so rich that you and your two guests could each take one-third (remember, that's like 1/2 a normal sandwich) and leave satisfied and the price'd be less than $4.50 per. Think of it like that and you won't mind ponying up for it. It's a rich mess of sandwich that doesn't look impressive but likely took years off my life and if I die soon from cardiac arrest I'm blaming this sandwich but at least I'll die happy. I also sprung for a Frangipane Croissant ($5), frangipane being a fancy name for "almond paste". This one I shared with the folks back home but not until after dinner at which time, some 7 hours after purchase, it was harder than desired. Butter hardens, right? I know this thing was great when I bought it but pastries are designed for immediate consumption. The aroma wafting through Tartine is almost comically luscious. It's impossible to stand in line inhaling that scent and then not over-purchase which explains my $25+ "lunch". Believe the hype; this place is great.

PROBLEM IS, you aren't necessarily given the opportunity to visualize their full selection.     -- The morning bun, which I think you can only buy in the afternoon (why call it morning bun?!) is also another well-known item.
    -- Food isn't that great. Just stick to the baked goods.

    Tartine means "slice of bread" in French. Although this bakery is not cheap (expect to pay $4 and up for pastries) the high-quality is worth it. My friend went a little crazy and got 2-3 of the following:

    Morning Bun
    Almond Croissants
    Chocolate Croissants
    Regular Croissants
    Bread Pudding

    Can you tell we like croissants? I LOVED the almond and chocolate ones. They're of a decent size and so flaky (in a good way). They are darker in color as well, so they LOOK burnt, but are crispy outside and soft inside.

    This is a very popular bakery so there was a line when we went on an early Sunday morning and waited for about 20 minutes to order.

    I would definitely come here again for the croissants. There was plenty in the display case as well!

    Welcome to carb heaven. There is always a line and for good reason.

    Banana Cream Tart - Life-changing. Even if you don't like pie (a concept that doesn't quite make sense to me), order this anyway. Trust me.

    Morning Bun - Perhaps the bestseller and I can see why. If you like oranges and sugar, definitely get this.

    Bread Pudding - The "bread" was more like an eggy custard than actual bread. It was unexpected but absolutely delicious.

    Mushroom Croque Monsieur - Cheesy and delicious. The tart tomato undercuts the greasiness of the cheese perfectly.

    Hazelnut Tart - I was expecting a creamy filling, but found that it was more of a brownie. Not a fan.

    Hands down my favorite bakery in SF.
